    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1967-10-18T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1967-10-18T18:00:00-05:00" n="553"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d553">
                <head>553. Memorandum From the President’s Special Assistant (<persName
                        corresp="#p_RWW_1">Rostow</persName>) to President <persName
                        corresp="#p_JLB_1">Johnson</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d553fn1">Source: <persName corresp="#p_JLB_1"
                            >Johnson</persName> Library, National Security File, Memos to the
                        President, <persName corresp="#p_RWW_1">Walt W. Rostow</persName>, Vol. 46.
                        Confidential.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1967-10-18T19:00:00-04:00">October 18, 1967, 7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>PL 480 Sales to the Congo</item>
                </list>
                <p>In the attached,<note n="2" xml:id="d553fn2">An October 2 memorandum from <gloss
                            target="#t_AID_1">AID</gloss> Administrator <persName corresp="#p_GWS_1"
                            >William Gaud</persName> and Acting Secretary of Agriculture John A.
                        Schnittker and an October 13 memorandum from Budget Director Charles L.
                        Schultze are attached but not printed.</note> Messrs. Schnittker, <persName
                        corresp="#p_GWS_1">Gaud</persName> and Schultze recommend a $13.4 million PL
                    480 agreement with the Congo. State and Treasury concur. The specifics:</p>
                <pb facs="0835" n="802" xml:id="pg_802"/>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">Commodities:</p>
                <p>Wheat flour—48,000 tons (equal to 67,000 tons of unmilled wheat)</p>
                <p>Cotton—19,000 bales</p>
                <p>Tobacco—3,000 tons</p>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">Credit Terms:</p>
                <p>Repayable in dollars, 20-year maturity with a 2-year grace period, 2½% interest
                    rate.</p>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">Budgetary Costs:</p>
                <p>These amounts <hi rend="italic">are</hi> provided for in our export targets and
                    budget estimates. No additional cost.</p>
                <p>This food is frankly designed to tide the Congo over the current crisis. There
                    are no new self-help terms attached. The mercenary problem has created a
                    critical supply situation for the Congolese. Production and transport of
                    agricultural products have fallen off badly. They haven’t gotten as much copper
                    out of Katanga as they had hoped, so their export earnings are likely to be
                    quite a bit lower than planned. Despite all this, Mobuto has put into effect a
                    comprehensive program of economic reforms—including a devaluation. He badly
                    needs this support to hold the line.</p>
                <p>As soon as it is safe, we will send out an <gloss target="#t_AID_1"
                    >AID</gloss>/Agriculture team to survey the self-help situation and will
                    determine where we can usefully put more leverage.</p>
                <p rend="right">
                    <hi rend="strong">Walt</hi>
                </p>
                <p>Approve<note n="3" xml:id="d553fn3">Next to this option is a notation on the
                        original in <persName corresp="#p_JLB_1">Johnson</persName>’s handwriting
                        that reads: “I suppose that’s all right.”</note>
                </p>
                <p>Disapprove</p>
                <p>Speak to me</p>
            </div>
